                <h2>Letter P</h2>
                <p>The 'P' in ASL is a mirrored version of the letter 'K'. It involves extending the middle and index
                    fingers to create a right angle, with the thumb extended between them, and then turning the hand so
                    that the palm is facing downwards.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, palm facing sideways, and
                        fingers spread apart.</li>
                    <li><strong>Index and Middle Fingers:</strong> Raise your index and middle fingers while keeping
                        them together. Then, split them to form a right angle, with the index finger pointing upwards
                        and the middle finger pointing forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb up between the index and middle fingers,
                        touching the middle segment of the middle finger. The thumb acts as a support, maintaining the
                        right angle position.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Other Fingers:</strong> Curl your ring and pinky fingers into your palm. They
                        should be held firmly against the palm, out of sight, to highlight the shape of the 'P'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Orientation:</strong> Rotate your hand so that the palm faces downwards, maintaining the
                        right angle and thumb position. This orientation is crucial to represent the letter 'P'
                        correctly.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Maintain the right angle and thumb positioning clearly. The
                        hand should be steady, and the sign held at eye level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practice the 'P' sign multiple times to ensure precision. This letter, with its unique hand
                    orientation, is an essential part of the ASL alphabet.</p>
