                <h2>Letter Q</h2>
                <p>The 'Q' in ASL is similar to the 'G' sign but with a different orientation. It involves pointing the
                    index finger downward while the thumb extends outward, and the remaining fingers are curled into the
                    palm.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, palm facing down.</li>
                    <li><strong>Index Finger Extension:</strong> Extend your index finger straight down, pointing
                        towards the ground.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Extend your thumb outwards, perpendicular to the index
                        finger.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Other Fingers:</strong> Curl your middle, ring, and pinky fingers into your
                        palm. Ensure they are tightly held to avoid confusion with other signs.</li>
                    <li><strong>Hand Orientation:</strong> Turn your hand so that your palm faces sideways, maintaining
                        the extended thumb and pointed index finger.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Keep the 'Q' sign clear by maintaining the downward direction
                        of the index finger and the outward position of the thumb. The hand should be steady, and the
                        sign held at a comfortable level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practicing the 'Q' sign is crucial for its distinct orientation and structure. Repeat the formation
                    several times, ensuring accuracy and clarity.</p>
