                <h2>Letter R</h2>
                <p>The 'R' in ASL is formed by crossing the index and middle fingers, similar to the common gesture for
                    'good luck' or 'crossing fingers.' The thumb is kept alongside the palm while the other fingers are
                    curled in.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Begin with your hand open, fingers extended, and palm
                        facing forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Crossing Fingers:</strong> Cross your index finger over your middle finger. The crossing
                        should be near the base of the fingers, not at the tips.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Position:</strong> Keep your thumb in its natural position, resting alongside your
                        palm. It should not be extended or overly pronounced.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Other Fingers:</strong> Curl your ring and pinky fingers into your palm. They
                        should be held tightly to avoid confusion with other signs.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Make sure the crossing of the index and middle fingers is
                        distinct and the hand is steady. The sign should be held at eye level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practice the 'R' sign multiple times to ensure it is easily recognizable. This letter is important in
                    ASL finger spelling and can be used in various ASL signs.</p>
