                <h2>Letter S</h2>
                <p>The 'S' in ASL is made by forming a fist with the thumb placed across the front of the curled
                    fingers. This sign is similar to the universal sign for a fist or strength, but the position of the
                    thumb is crucial for it to represent the letter 'S'.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, palm facing yourself, and
                        fingers spread apart.</li>
                    <li><strong>Forming the Fist:</strong> Curl your fingers into your palm to make a fist.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb across the front of your curled fingers,
                        typically over or touching the middle finger.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Ensure that the thumb is correctly positioned across the
                        fingers and that the fist is tight enough to be clear and distinguishable as the letter 'S'.
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Steady Hand:</strong> Keep your hand steady and the fist firm. The sign should be held
                        at eye level for visibility and clear communication.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practice forming the 'S' sign to ensure its clarity and recognition. This letter is a fundamental
                    part of the ASL alphabet and is widely used in various signs.</p>
