                <h2>Letter T</h2>
                <p>The 'T' in ASL is represented by tucking the thumb between the index and middle fingers, with the
                    rest of the fingers curled into the palm. This sign requires careful placement of the thumb to
                    accurately represent the letter 'T'.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, all fingers extended, and
                        palm facing yourself.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb under your index finger, resting it between
                        the index and middle fingers. The tip of the thumb should slightly protrude between the two
                        fingers.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Fingers:</strong> Curl your index, middle, ring, and pinky fingers into your
                        palm, securing the thumb in place.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Make sure the thumb is correctly positioned and visible between
                        the index and middle fingers. The fingers should be tightly curled over the thumb to distinctly
                        form the letter 'T'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Steady Hand:</strong> Keep your hand steady and the sign held at eye level for
                        visibility. The formation should be clear and easily recognizable as the letter 'T'.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practicing the 'T' sign is important for its unique structure in the ASL alphabet. Repeat the
